Manuscript Number: PHYCOM-D-20-00042R2 &#8239;

Dragonfly Approach for Resource Allocation in Industrial Wireless Networks &#8239;

Dear Professor Kim,

Thank you for submitting your manuscript to Physical Communication. 

I am pleased to inform you that your manuscript has been accepted for publication. &#8239; 

My comments, and any reviewer comments, are below.&#8239; &#8239;  
Your accepted manuscript will now be transferred to our production department. We will create a proof which you will be asked to check, and you will also be asked to complete a number of online forms required for publication. If we need additional information from you during the production process, we will contact you directly.

We appreciate you submitting your manuscript to Physical Communication and hope you will consider us again for future submissions.

Kind regards, &#8239; &#8239; 
Professor Michalis Matthaiou &#8239; 
Editor-in-Chief

Physical Communication

Editor and Reviewer comments: Before submitting the camera-ready version, make sure to address the remaining comments.

Reviewer #1: The authors have successfully addressed the reviewers comments.


Reviewer #2: The authors have fairly addressed my comments in the subsequent revisions. Furthermore, I have the following comments to improve its quality for acceptance.
- The equations are not yet expressed properly. Furthermore, throughout the manuscript, the authors should use &#34;, where&#34; instead of &#34;, Where&#34; after defining the equations.
- In (4), &#34; Therefore, SINR estimations for the relay node $k$ is given by&#34;. Please merge (4) and (5) and then define the variables.
- You have not clearly defined latency L in (6). You supposedly mean the overall latency for RN_k, \forall k ? Please clearly mention what exactly is the latency based objective function, what you are trying to do (minimize the overall latency? (7)), in reference with (4)-(7).
- In (19), it should be p_j , not p_m.
- Eqn (28) is vague. How the criteria for selection is defined?  The normalizing factors adding up to 1 is not clear to me. The authors should provide any references, or discussions to clarify?
 &#8239;

Manuscript Number: ICTE-D-20-00040 &#8239; 

Deep Reinforcement Learning with Edge Computing in Faulty-Node Detection for Industrial Internet of Things 

Dear Professor Kim,

Thank you for submitting your manuscript to ICT Express. 

I regret to inform you that the reviewers recommend against publishing your manuscript, and I must therefore reject it. My comments, and any reviewer comments, are below.&#8239; &#8239;

For alternative journals that may be more suitable for your manuscript, please refer to our Journal Finder (http://journalfinder.elsevier.com).

We appreciate you submitting your manuscript to ICT Express and thank you for giving us the opportunity to consider your work. &#8239;

Kind regards, &#8239; &#8239; 
Mostafa Zaman Chowdhury &#8239; 
Editor &#8239;

ICT Express &#8239;

Editor and Reviewer comments: &#8239; &#8239; 
Reviewer #1: In the paper &#39;Deep Reinforcement Learning with Edge Computing in Faulty-Node Detection for Industrial Internet of Things&#39;, authors propose to use RL to detect faulty node in edge computing environment, in specific, it utilizes the battery level data, via simulation, it claims &#39;The simulation results indicate that the reliability of the proposed scheme is higher than those of the traditional schemes&#39;. Other contributions claimed include &#39;reduce the processing time and network latency&#39;, and faulty-node-detection accuracy.

However, the first and foremost concern I have for the paper is unclarity of the problem definition, and why RL is necessary. The 4-page paper dedicates 1.5 pages for the background knowledge of MDP and RL, without linking it to the problem to be solved by the paper. Further excluding some space for title/author and references, the remaining content of the paper failed to convey what is unique and novel about the proposed research. It need to clearly define what type of fault for IOT nodes the paper want to detect, without which, it is really hard to see why a simple rule or heuristics-based approach, e.g. by checking the battery level reported, cannot solve the problem.

Besides, the paper is also lacking the details about what is the metrics for evaluating, although it claims it deliver better accuracy, reliability reduced time and latency, than traditional approaches. I didn&#39;t see clearly how the evaluations is done, and where are the comparisons with the traditional approaches.

In short, a suggestion is to clearly define the problem, clearly present how the defined problem is modeled using in the RL approach. And a detailed description of the evaluations and comparisons with the baseline are needed.


Reviewer #2: The authors study the problem of faulty node detection for industrial Internet of things by leveraging the technologies affects computing and the deep reinforcement learning mechanism. The provided theoretical analysis is concrete, complete, and correct. The authors have well thought out their main contributions and the manuscript is overall well written. The authors should consider the following comments in order to improve the quality of presentation of their manuscript, as well as some suggestions by the reviewer in order to improve the scientific depth of the manuscript.

1. Initially, prospect theory has been introduced in the literature, such as Vamvakas, P., et al. &#34;Exploiting prospect theory and risk-awareness to protect UAV-assisted network operation.&#34; EURASIP Journal on Wireless Communications and Networking 2019.1 (2019): 286, in order to detect faulty nodes within a wireless communications system. Furthermore, machine learning approaches, such as Huang, Xin-Lin, Xiaomin Ma, and Fei Hu. &#34;Machine learning and intelligent communications.&#34; Mobile Networks and Applications 23.1 (2018): 68-70, have been also exploited in order to detect faulty nodes within a wireless sensor network. The authors are encouraged to discuss those two different types of approaches that have been introduced in the literature on top of the one examined in this paper.

2. In section 3, the authors should provide some more detailed theoretical discussion regarding the adopted deep reinforcement learning mechanism. The current provided discussion is very limited in order to enable the reader to reproduce the provided theoretical analysis.

3. In section 4, the authors should provide some indicative numerical results showing the real execution time of the proposed framework and discuss its potential to be applied in real time or even close to real-time manner in a real industrial Internet of things environment.

4. In section 4, the authors should provide a scalability analysis in order to show the scalability and robustness of the proposed framework in a real industrial Internet of things environment.

5. Finally, the overall manuscript should be checked for typos, syntax, and grammar errors in order to improve the quality of its presentation.




Reviewer #3: In this paper, the authors claim that they propose a novel faulty-node-detection scheme for IIoT that leverages edge computing and deep reinforcement learning (DRL); edge computing is used to reduce the processing time and network latency by
performing a DRL task. On the whole, I am not seeing any real contributions made by this work. There is no novel algorithm proposed. The whole work is not well written, which is not technical sounds.

